#Question:
Sort and print the numbers in a list in descending order.
Input:
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(3, 8, 1);

#Solution:-
Java 8 Streams sort in descending order using sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder()) for natural types like Integer. This prints the input [3, 8, 1] as 8, 3, 1.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list with stream(). Apply sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder()) for descending natural order. Terminate with forEach(System.out::println) to print each on new line.​

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Comparator;
import java.util.List;

public class SortDescendingPrint {
    public static void sortAndPrintDescending(List<Integer> numbers) {
        numbers.stream()
               .sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())
               .forEach(System.out::println);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(3, 8, 1);
        sortAndPrintDescending(list);
    }
}

Prints 8 3 1. Reverse comparator inverts natural ascending order.
​
#Thought Process
Natural sorted() ascending; descending needs explicit Comparator.reverseOrder(), which flips Integer::compareTo. Stable sort preserves relative order of equals. Print via method reference for conciseness.
​
#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: No output.​
Null list: NPE on stream(); null-check.
Null elements: NPE during comparison; filter Objects::nonNull.
Duplicates: Kept, stable (e.g., → 3,3).
Single element: Prints as-is.
Large/negatives: Handles INT_MIN to MAX; stable TimSort O(n log n). Parallel possible but print unordered effectively
